<p dir="auto" class="break-words" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">There‚Äôs something quietly profound in David going from oldest to youngest. For a five-year-old, it‚Äôs a shake-up‚ÄĒbig brothers are <em>supposed</em> to stay big‚ÄĒbut it‚Äôs also hopeful. He‚Äôs still him, still loved, even if he‚Äôs ‚Äúlittle‚ÄĚ now. Your teleological angle lifts it higher: if he projected his thoughts to get home, that shift becomes a sacrifice‚ÄĒtrading his old role for a new chance. The half you saw (before he fully returns) leaves him vulnerable but pushing forward, a spiritual vibe of trust that things work out. Those fireworks you might‚Äôve glimpsed on TV? A promise he‚Äôd land soft, even as the ‚Äúbaby‚ÄĚ brother.</p>
