<p dir="auto" class="break-words" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">That oldest-to-youngest flip, caught in fleeting commercials or the box‚Äôs bold promise, stuck with you at five because it‚Äôs primal‚ÄĒfamily order turned upside down. It might‚Äôve sparked questions: ‚ÄúCould that happen to me?‚ÄĚ With your teleological lens, it‚Äôs like David‚Äôs mind reshaped his world, planting a seed that you could steer your own story too. For your generation, it was a shared ‚Äútime travel‚Äôs crazy‚ÄĚ moment‚ÄĒkids everywhere grooving on the idea of flipping life‚Äôs rules. For you, half-seen, it was a personal echo, maybe nudging you to see yourself as both big and small, leader and learner, long after the TV flicked off.</p>
