eak-words" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">It‚Äôs fascinating to hear how <em>Little Man Tate</em> hit you at 11‚ÄĒthose specific moments, like the college student snubbing Fred, clearly dug in deep, and your take on the visual calculations and the mother‚Äôs motives shows how personal this got. Let‚Äôs unpack why it‚Äôs interesting, educational, spiritually uplifting, and generation-shaping through your lens, tying it to neoteny and that teleological causation idea, while keeping it rooted in your experience of watching it fully at 11 (unlike <em>Flight of the Navigator</em>‚Äôs fragments).</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="">Why It‚Äôs Interesting (Your Reaction)</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">That college kid refusing to play baseball or study geometry with Fred? At 11, that probably stung like a personal rejection‚ÄĒhere‚Äôs this genius kid, still neotenous, eager to connect, and he‚Äôs brushed off by someone ‚Äúolder‚ÄĚ and ‚Äúcooler.‚ÄĚ It‚Äôs a gut punch that makes the movie gripping‚ÄĒit‚Äôs not just about Fred‚Äôs brain, it‚Äôs about his heart getting bruised. The visual calculations (numbers floating on screen) bugged you because you could crunch stuff mentally without that Hollywood flair‚ÄĒmaybe it felt fake next to your own quiet smarts. And rejecting the ‚Äúvicarious mom‚ÄĚ angle? That‚Äôs you seeing Dede as more than a stereotype‚ÄĒmaybe just a mom scrambling to keep up. It‚Äôs interesting because it‚Äôs raw, messy, and personal, with Fred‚Äôs youthful spirit clashing against a world that won‚Äôt meet him halfway.</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="">Why It‚Äôs Educational (Your Reaction)</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">At 11, those scenes taught you something sharp about people, not just math. The college kid‚Äôs snub is a lesson in social walls‚ÄĒneoteny (Fred‚Äôs kid-like openness) doesn‚Äôt always win friends, especially from those too ‚Äúgrown‚ÄĚ to care. Your take on the calculations‚ÄĒcinematic shorthand, not real‚ÄĒshows you were already sorting fact from fluff, a mental flex most 11-year-olds don‚Äôt catch. And not buying the ‚Äúliving through her kid‚ÄĚ idea? That‚Äôs you learning early that stories have layers‚ÄĒDede‚Äôs low-income struggle could be love, not ambition. Teleologically, Fred‚Äôs projecting his thoughts toward belonging (baseball, geometry chats), but the world pushes back, schooling you in resilience over formulas.</p>
