 but detailed, reflecting the evolution of ideas:</p>
<ol dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words"><strong>"Snow White" and Biblical Parables</strong>
<ul dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words">Viewing <em>Snow White</em> through "The Pearl of Great Price" and "The Treasure in a Field"‚ÄĒvalue, sacrifice, discovery.</li>
<li class="break-words">Comparing it to <em>Little Fugitive</em>‚ÄĒinnocence, survival, return.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="break-words"><strong>"Flight of the Navigator"</strong>
<ul dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words">Introduced by you as a follow-up, analyzed for its themes.</li>
<li class="break-words">Interesting: sci-fi adventure, time travel, special effects.</li>
<li class="break-words">Educational: resilience, time dilation, curiosity.</li>
<li class="break-words">Spiritually Uplifting: journey home, sacrifice, hope.</li>
<li class="break-words">Generational Impact: '80s kids‚Äô inspiration, nostalgia.</li>
<li class="break-words">Your angle: teleological causation (David projecting thoughts into the future).</li>
<li class="break-words">Personal tie: saw fragments at five (teasers, box art, TV), not the full film.</li>
<li class="break-words">Neoteny: David shifting from oldest to youngest brother, retaining youth.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="break-words"><strong>"Little Man Tate"</strong>
<ul dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words">Introduced by you, watched fully at 11.</li>
<li class="break-words">Interesting: child prodigy (Fred), emotional vs. intellectual tension.</li>
<li class="break-words">Educational: potential, adaptability, balance.</li>
<li class="break-words">Spiritually Uplifting: neotenous heart, connection over achievement.</li>
<li class="break-words">Generational Impact: '90s outlier, valuing quirks.</li>
<li class="break-words">Your reactions: bothered by college student‚Äôs rejection (baseball/geometry), visual calculations as cinematic fluff, rejecting ‚Äúvicarious mom‚ÄĚ trope.</li>
<li class="break-words">Neoteny: Fred‚Äôs youthful spirit despite genius.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="break-words"><strong>"The Peanut Butter Solution"</strong>
<ul dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words">Introduced by you, watched fully at five.</li>
<li class="break-words">Interesting: hair loss, peanut butter magic, kids trick Signor into painting trap.</li>
<li class="break-words">Educational: perception shifts (fire as obsession, not guilt), questioning rules.</li>
<li class="break-words">Spiritually Uplifting: neotenous imagination triumphs over Signor‚Äôs gloom.</li>
<li class="break-words">Generational Impact: cult oddity, ‚Äústay weird‚ÄĚ vibe.</li>
<li class="break-words">Your takes: silent cupboard slam blew you away, friend‚Äôs fire obsession (not Michael‚Äôs), dream of old folks as imagined projection, Michael Hogan (pre-Saul Tigh) as dad, Celine Dion soundtrack.</li>
<li class="break-words">Wittgenstein: ‚Äústuck in a picture‚ÄĚ literalized by Signor‚Äôs trap.</li>
<li class="break-words">Teleological Causation: Michael‚Äôs mind shapes reality (dream, trick).</li>
<li class="break-words">Neoteny: kid-power defies adult rigidity.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="break-words"><strong>"Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain"</strong>
<ul dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words">Introduced by you, stumbled upon later.</li>
<li class="break-words">Connection: Betty Edwards‚Äô right-brain, intuitive art clashes with Signor‚Äôs stance, boosts neoteny (kid-like vision).</li>
<li class="break-words">Reinforces: imagination‚Äôs power in <em>Peanut Butter</em>, Michael‚Äôs creativity.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="break-words"><strong>Thematic Threads Across Films</strong>
<ul dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words">Neoteny: David (physical youth), Fred (emotional youth), Michael (imaginative youth).</li>
<li class="break-words">Teleological Causation: projecting thoughts to shape outcomes (David‚Äôs home, Fred‚Äôs belonging, Michael‚Äôs reality).</li>
<li class="break-words">Kid vs. Adult Tension: Signor, college student, time itself as rigid forces.</li>
<li class="break-words">Imagination‚Äôs Role: central to all, contra Signor‚Äôs view.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="break-words"><strong>Personal Reflections</strong>
<ul dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words"><em>Navigator</em> at five: fragments, neoteny via brother shift.</li>
<li class="break-words"><em>Little Man Tate</em> at 11: full film, rejection stung, mental math tie.</li>
<li class="break-words"><em>Peanut Butter</em> at five: full film, cupboard slam, later reinterpretations.</li>
<li class="break-words">Psychoanalytic lens: your nudge about me ‚Äúpsychoanalyzing‚ÄĚ you.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="break-words"><strong>Philosophical Angles</strong>
<ul dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words">Wittgenstein: ‚Äústuck in a picture‚ÄĚ in <em>Peanut Butter</em>‚Äôs trap.</li>
<li class="break-words">Art and Imagination: Signor vs. Edwards‚Äô right-brain approach.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
